{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits of controlling or excluding competitor or predator species from bee nesting sites?",
  "relevant_summary": "Excluding ants from solitary bee nesting sites has been shown to increase production of offspring, as demonstrated in one replicated controlled trial with the endemic Australian bee Exonuera nigrescens (Action 46). Studies of artificial nest sites for solitary bees document various threats from competitors and predators that affect reproductive success. Mortality rates from parasitism and predation in bee nest boxes range from 13% mortality for cavity-nesting bees and wasps combined in Germany to 56% mortality overall for the subtropical carpenter bee Xylocopa fenestrata in India, indicating significant impacts on bee populations (Action 47). The provision of nest boxes with appropriate design features to reduce parasitism has been shown to improve reproductive success, with one study demonstrating that reed stem and wooden grooved-board nest boxes produced more bees per nest than other types, while nest boxes with plastic-lined holes, plastic or paper tubes were much less productive due to parasitism or mould (Action 47). Competition from introduced species can also significantly impact native bee nesting success, as two replicated trials in California showed that introduced European earwigs and introduced European leafcutter bee species more commonly occupied nest boxes than native bees (Action 47).",
  "action_ids": [
    "46",
