{"query": "What are the known risks and control methods associated with using commercial bee colonies for pollination?", "summary": "Commercial bee colonies used for pollination face several identified risks and require specific control methods. Disease management is a primary concern, with Nosema bombi infection identified as a pathogen affecting managed bumblebee colonies, though antibiotic fumagillin has been found ineffective against this infection in Bombus occidentalis colonies (Action 42). Indian meal moth (Plodia interpunctella) represents another risk in commercial bumblebee colonies, which can be controlled using the insect pathogen Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt) Aizawai strain at a concentration of 1 g Bt/litre of water (Action 42).

The small hive beetle poses a significant threat during commercial honey bee transport, with research showing that more than half the beetles escaped from commercial Apis mellifera transport packages even when mite-killing strips were used for control (Action 41). 

For solitary bee management, several species in the family Megachilidae are reared commercially as pollinators for alfalfa and fruit trees, nesting in drilled wooden blocks or stacked grooved boards. However, parasites and pathogens are problematic in these operations, requiring the development of various control methods (Action 54). When rearing solitary bees artificially, high larval mortality occurs when Osmia cornuta is fed artificial pollen-based diets, including honey bee-collected pollen, while Megachile rotundata can be successfully reared on artificial diets based on honey bee-collected pollen, though synthetic pollen substitutes result in either death or low pre-pupal weight (Action 54).", "action_ids": ["42","41","54"]}

