  "relevant_summary": "A site comparison study in one city in the UK found more species of bumblebee in domestic city gardens with lower intensity of management, a measure reflecting the tidiness of the garden and the use of garden pesticides, though solitary bees were not affected by this measure (Action 2). Two replicated trials in the USA and Canada found more wild bees (either more species or more individuals) in gardens planted with bee forage or native plants, relative to conventionally managed gardens (Action 1). Another USA trial found more bee species after the addition of bee forage plants to a community garden (Action 1). Three trials in the UK or USA showed that native flowering plants or bee forage plants are well used by wild bees when planted in gardens (Action 1). A UK trial demonstrated that some popular non-native or horticulturally modified garden flowers are not frequently visited by insects, despite providing nectar in some cases (Action 1). Three of five replicated studies in Germany and the USA found that gardens planted with native species had a greater species richness of butterfly and moth adults and caterpillars than gardens with mixed or exclusively non-native plant species (Action 3842). Two of three replicated studies in the USA found that gardens planted with native species had a higher abundance of butterfly and moth caterpillars than gardens with mixed or exclusively non-native plant species (Action 3842). One replicated, site comparison study in France found that gardens where insecticides and herbicides were not used had a higher abundance of butterflies, but gardens where fungicides and snail pellets were not used had a lower abundance of butterflies (Action 3900).",
