{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effectiveness of increasing floral resources for bees at a landscape scale versus a local patch scale on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence comparing landscape scale versus local patch scale effectiveness for increasing floral resources for bees on farmland shows mixed findings. At the landscape scale, one large replicated controlled trial found that the average abundance of long-tongued bumblebees on field margins was positively correlated with the number of pollen and nectar agri-environment agreements in a 10 km grid square (Action 362, Action 21). At the local patch scale, fourteen trials in Europe and North America recorded substantial numbers of wild bees foraging on perennial or annual sown flowering plants in the agricultural environment, with ten trials finding substantial numbers of foraging wild bees on phacelia patches and six trials recording 8-35 bee species (Action 17). However, one replicated controlled trial in the UK showed that planted perennial leguminous herbs were more attractive to bumblebees in landscapes with a greater proportion of arable farming, suggesting landscape context influences local patch effectiveness (Action 17). Importantly, one trial in the Netherlands showed that bee numbers and species richness are not higher in farmland 50-1,500 m away from planted flower patches, indicating limited spatial spillover effects from local patches (Action 17). For reproductive success measures, one trial showed that planted patches of bigleaf lupine in commercial apple orchards significantly enhanced the reproductive success of blue orchard mason bees, but two trials in Germany found no or relatively few species of solitary bee nesting on set-aside fields sown with phacelia or clover (Action 17).",
